  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I recover data from my broken iPhone?",
  "response": "Recovering data from a broken iPhone can be a challenging task, but there are several methods you can try depending on the extent of the damage and whether the iPhone is operational. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to help you recover your data:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Assess the Damage**\n   - **Screen Damage**: If the screen is cracked or unresponsive but the phone still powers on, you may be able to recover data using a computer or external accessories.\n   - **Physical Damage**: If the iPhone is bent, water-damaged, or otherwise physically compromised, proceed cautiously to avoid further harm.\n   - **No Power**: If the iPhone does not turn on, the internal hardware may be damaged, and professional assistance may be required.\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Backup from iCloud**\n   - If you\u2019ve previously enabled iCloud backups, your data may already be stored in the cloud.\n   - Log in to iCloud.com with your Apple ID to check for photos, contacts, notes, and other synced data.\n   - If you have a recent backup, you can restore it to a new iPhone.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Connect to a Computer**\n   - Use a USB cable to connect your broken iPhone to a computer (Mac or Windows) that you\u2019ve previously synced with.\n   - If the phone is recognized, you can use **Finder** (on Mac) or **iTunes** (on Windows) to back up your data.\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Use iTunes/Finder Backup**\n   - Open **Finder** (Mac) or **iTunes** (Windows) once your iPhone is connected.\n   - Select your iPhone from the device list and click **Back Up Now** to create a backup of your data.\n   - You can restore this backup to a new iPhone later.\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Use Recovery Software**\n   - If your iPhone is not recognized by iTunes/Finder, you can use third-party recovery tools like **iMobie PhoneRescue**, **Tenorshare UltData**, or **Dr.Fone**.\n   - These tools can extract data directly from the iPhone or from an existing backup.\n\n---\n\n### 6. **Use an External Display**\n   - If the screen is broken but the phone is still functional, connect your iPhone to an external display using a Lightning-to-HDMI adapter or a wireless solution like Apple TV.\n   - This allows you to navigate the iPhone and back up your data.\n\n---\n\n### 7. **Seek Professional Help**\n   - If your iPhone is severely damaged or you\u2019re unable to recover data on your own, contact **Apple Support** or visit an **Apple Authorized Service Provider**.\n   - Data recovery specialists may also be able to retrieve data from a broken iPhone, but this can be costly.\n\n---\n\n### 8. **Use Emergency Contacts**\n   - If you cannot access your iPhone, ensure that your emergency contacts (e.g., family members) have access to your iCloud credentials to help recover data.\n\n---\n\n### Tips to Prevent Future Data Loss:\n   - Regularly back up your iPhone to iCloud or your computer.\n   - Enable **iCloud Photos** to automatically sync your photos and videos.\n   - Use **iCloud Drive** for important documents and files.\n\nBy following these steps, you should be able to recover most, if not all, of your data from your broken iPhone.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
